     1	/**
     2	 * HEADER POLICY binding (plan v3.3 §HEADER POLICY, decided 2026-07-12).
     3	 *
     4	 * Binds docs/header-policy-2026-07-12.md to the shipped file: public/_headers
     5	 * exists, parses as Cloudflare Pages `_headers` syntax, applies EXACTLY the
     6	 * four adopted headers to `/*`, and carries NO Content-Security-Policy — the
     7	 * CSP deferral is part of the policy (it cannot be verified by the artifact
     8	 * battery; see the record §3), so a CSP appearing here without a new reviewed
     9	 * decision is a failure, not an upgrade.
    10	 */
    11	import { readFileSync } from "node:fs";
    12	import { join } from "node:path";
    13	import { describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
    14	
    15	const HEADERS_PATH = join(process.cwd(), "public", "_headers");
    16	
    17	const ADOPTED: Record<string, string> = {
    18	  "X-Content-Type-Options": "nosniff",
    19	  "X-Frame-Options": "DENY",
    20	  "Referrer-Policy": "no-referrer",
    21	  "Permissions-Policy": "camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()",
    22	};
    23	
    24	function parse(): { rules: Array<{ url: string; headers: Array<[string, string]> }> } {
    25	  const raw = readFileSync(HEADERS_PATH, "utf8");
    26	  const rules: Array<{ url: string; headers: Array<[string, string]> }> = [];
    27	  for (const line of raw.split("\n")) {
    28	    if (line.trim() === "" || line.trim().startsWith("#")) continue;
    29	    if (/^\S/.test(line)) {
    30	      rules.push({ url: line.trim(), headers: [] });
    31	      continue;
    32	    }
    33	    const m = line.trim().match(/^([A-Za-z0-9-]+):\s*(.*)$/);
    34	    if (!m) throw new Error(`unparseable _headers line: ${JSON.stringify(line)}`);
    35	    const last = rules[rules.length - 1];
    36	    if (!last) throw new Error(`header line before any URL rule: ${JSON.stringify(line)}`);
    37	    last.headers.push([m[1], m[2]]);
    38	  }
    39	  return { rules };
    40	}
    41	
    42	describe("header policy — public/_headers is exactly the adopted 2026-07-12 policy", () => {
    43	  it("exists, has one /* rule, and parses", () => {
    44	    const { rules } = parse();
    45	    expect(rules).toHaveLength(1);
    46	    expect(rules[0].url).toBe("/*");
    47	  });
    48	
    49	  it("carries exactly the four adopted headers with exactly the adopted values", () => {
    50	    const { rules } = parse();
    51	    const got = Object.fromEntries(rules[0].headers);
    52	    expect(got).toEqual(ADOPTED);
    53	  });
    54	
    55	  it("carries no CSP anywhere (the deferral is policy, not an omission)", () => {
    56	    const raw = readFileSync(HEADERS_PATH, "utf8");
    57	    // Match the header NAME position only — the comment naming the deferral may
    58	    // mention CSP in prose; an actual header line must not.
    59	    for (const line of raw.split("\n")) {
    60	      if (line.trim().startsWith("#")) continue;
    61	      expect(/content-security-policy/i.test(line)).toBe(false);
    62	    }
    63	  });
    64	
    65	  it("the policy record exists and names the CSP deferral", () => {
     1	# HEADER POLICY — Cloudflare Pages response headers (2026-07-12, plan v3.3)
     2	
     3	**Decision:** ship a source-controlled [`public/_headers`](../public/_headers) applying four low-risk security headers to every path, and **defer a Content-Security-Policy with a named reason**. Decided and committed BEFORE batch E so the review covers it; no header change may enter the release candidate after review.
     4	
     5	## 1 · Source basis (live, dated)
     6	
     7	- Cloudflare Pages `_headers` reference — <https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/headers/>, fetched **2026-07-12**: the file lives in the project's static asset directory (for frameworks, `public/`); `[url]` line + indented `name: value` pairs; splat matching; ≤100 rules; the file itself is not served. Direct-upload projects are served the same way (the file ships inside the uploaded directory — ours is `out/`).
     8	- Next.js static export (`output: "export"`, our `next.config`) copies `public/*` verbatim into `out/` — so the policy is one committed file, present in the immutable artifact the release gate hashes.
     9	
    10	## 2 · Adopted headers (all paths, `/*`)
    11	
    12	| Header | Value | Why |
    13	| --- | --- | --- |
    14	| `X-Content-Type-Options` | `nosniff` | Blocks MIME sniffing; zero behavioral risk on a static site. |
    15	| `X-Frame-Options` | `DENY` | Nothing legitimately embeds this site; kills clickjacking framing. |
    16	| `Referrer-Policy` | `no-referrer` | Maximal privacy for visitors following the few outbound links (GitHub, USPTO); the site itself needs no referrer data. |
    17	| `Permissions-Policy` | `camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()` | The site uses none of these; explicit denial is free. |
    18	
    19	## 3 · CSP — deferred, with the reason named
    20	
    21	A strict CSP would be the strongest browser-level enforcement of the site's zero-external-requests claim — and is exactly the kind of change that must not ship unverified:
    22	
    23	1. **Our release battery cannot exercise it.** The artifact-mode e2e serves the recorded `out/` through a local static server that does not read `_headers` — a CSP that broke Next's hydration inline scripts (`__NEXT_DATA__` et al.) would pass every pre-deploy gate and ship broken. Verification-before-claims (RULES §3) says don't adopt what we can't test.
    24	2. **Report-Only is not an option here:** a report endpoint is an external request, which the site's own posture forbids.
    25	3. The four adopted headers carry no such risk (none affects script execution or asset loading).
    26	
    27	**Path to adoption (future, owner-gated like any consequential change):** verify a candidate CSP on a *preview* deployment (real Pages headers, real browser), then commit it through a reviewed slice. Until then, no CSP header and no CSP claim.
    28	
    29	## 4 · Verification
    30	
    31	- **Now (pre-deploy):** `evals/packs/header-policy.test.ts` binds this policy — the file exists in `public/`, parses, carries exactly the four adopted headers with exactly these values, and carries no CSP (the deferral is part of the policy).
    32	- **At S8 (owner-gated deploy):** the preview smoke asserts each adopted header is actually served (plan §S8 "headers verified"); production re-smoke repeats it.
    33	- **Honest boundary:** until a deploy happens, these headers are *committed policy*, not *observed behavior* — the live site (already several slices behind) serves none of them today.
     1	# Demo record — 2026-07 (S7, plan v3.3)
     2	
     3	**What this is:** the committed record of one complete run of every `docs/SHOWCASE.md` command, executed **verbatim as published**, with captured transcripts and exit codes. It exists so a reviewer can see what the showcase actually does without running it — and so the showcase's own commands are periodically proven runnable.
